<TITLE> Main Titas gas line explodes in Savar </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Savar, Jan 24 (bdnews24.com)  The main line of Titas Gas that feeds the capital city burst and caught fire Thursday when a sand-laden trawler hit it on the Turag River near Amin Bazar in Savar in the morning. The flames leaped as high as 150-200 feet and burnt six cables of the main line of Rural Electrification Board (REB), spreading panic in the adjoining area. Six hours into the incident, Titas Gas authorities stopped the gas connection, causing low gas pressure in several city areas. Police have seized the trawler. The trawler of Sharmin Enterprise hit the gas pipe in Turag River on its way from Ashulia to Amin Bazar around 8:30am. The pipe burst with a loud bang and caught fire. Director, Operations, of Titas Gas Transmission and Distribution Company Ltd Aminur Rahman said gas connections from Mirpur and Ashulia stations were severed at about 1.45 pm. It caused gas pressure to go down in Shyamoli, Hajaribagh, Mohammadpur and some adjoining areas in the city and it would continue for sometime, he said. Titas Gas's Savar office manager Joynal Abedin said they had made moves to repair the pipe with the help of divers, which would take some days. Gas pressure in Savar would also remained down, he added. Rezaul Haq, junior assistant manager (Preservation) of REB Dhaka unit, Amin Bazar grid, said six cables of the main line burnt as the flames had gone up to 200 feet. He said they had estimated the loss at about Tk 10 lakh. Touhidul Islam, assistant sub-inspector of Savar Police Station who was on the scene, said the sand-filled trawler had been seized. If Titas Gas authorities filed complaint, a case would be lodged. He said the households in the adjoining areas had not suffered any damage in the incident. bdnews2
